{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496551","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496551"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:50:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:50:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1381"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1381","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1381"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.15,0.19,0.02,0.6]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1381"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"37749"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1381","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1381"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1381"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"22307"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"29"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"393"},{"type":"tags","id":"498"},{"type":"tags","id":"1109"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4230"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9091"},{"type":"tags","id":"9097"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7906"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9114"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"37749","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/37749"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 50-year-old woman presents to the emergency department with a two-week history of intermittent colicky abdominal pain. She has experienced a recent change in her bowel habit, with episodes of diarrhoea and constipation. Her history includes hypertension, colonoscopic removal of an adenomatous polyp and excision of a melanoma from her back 15 years ago. A diagnosis of a small bowel obstruction is made and this does not resolve with conservative management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA laparotomy is performed and the following finding made (Image 1). The opened specimen of the small bowel is shown (Image 2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Small bowel lipoma","Carcinoma of the caecum","Gastrointestinal stromal tumour","Lymphoma","Metastatic melanoma"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe first photograph shows an intussusception. Depending on the cause, an intussusception can be transient and this could well explain the patient\u0027s symptoms. Any of the listed conditions could cause an intussusception, where the pathological process is usually at the apex of the intussusception within the intussuscipiens. The structure shown in the second photograph is heavily pigmented, making the diagnosis of \u003Cstrong\u003Emetastatic melanoma\u003C/strong\u003E most likely. Even though this patient\u0027s original melanoma was excised 15 years ago, there can be a long interval before metastatic disease appears. The gastrointestinal tract is a relatively common site for metastatic disease and melanoma should be considered in the diagnosis of any patient who presents with abdominal pain and a history of skin cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELipomas \u003C/strong\u003Ecan develop at many sites in the body and the gut is a well recognised site. Whilst most would probably never produce any symptoms, an intussusception is a well recognised mode of presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarcinoma of the caecum \u003C/strong\u003Eshould always be considered in cases of small bowel obstruction, although the process of intussusception would be uncommon.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGastrointestinal stromal tumours (GIST)\u003C/strong\u003E are relatively uncommon lesions and many are only found incidentally. However, when they do cause symptoms, these are usually those associated with chronic blood loss or obstruction. When situated in the small bowel a GIST may present with small bowel obstruction and intussusception. In this case, the heavy pigmentation is more suggestive of melanoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Elymphomas\u003C/strong\u003E can involve the gastrointestinal tract and present with intestinal obstruction, the patient will usually also have symptoms such as weight loss, fatigue and night sweats.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The lag time for metastatic disease to present after excision of a primary cutaneous melanoma can be many years and can occur virtually anywhere in the body including the digestive tract."],"references":["[Internet]. StatPearls [database on the Internet]. Melanoma. [cited 2023 Apr 4]. Available from: https://www.google.com/search?q=melanoma+statpearls\u0026rlz=1C1GCEA_enSY955SY955\u0026oq=melanoma+statpearls\u0026aqs=chrome..69i57.4945j0j1\u0026sourceid=chrome\u0026ie=UTF-8"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"22307"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1381"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19851"},{"type":"media","id":"19852"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19851","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19851"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/5f6fb704-2f23-4526-b2b5-0f8e206f6778.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/5f6fb704-2f23-4526-b2b5-0f8e206f6778.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"media","id":"19852","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19852"},"attrib